<!-- Main Page Begins -->
 <div class="welcome">Welcome to ECS, the School  of Electronics and Computer Science at the University of Southampton. ECS is one of the world's leading centres for <a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/research/">research</a>, <a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/about/teaching/">teaching</a>, <a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/business/">enterprise and innovation</a> in Electronics, Electrical Engineering and Computer Science.  <div class="sig">Head of School: <a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/people/wh">Professor Wendy Hall</a></div> </div> <div class="headline"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/873"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_873_img&amp;maxw=200&amp;maxh=150&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=21d584eecc523658be17d8c65bc48138&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Professor Neil White" title="Professor Neil White (Copyright: Grant Lynch)" border="0" width="200" height="130" class="thumbnail" /></a><h2 class="hide">Headline News</h2><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/873">£2.2 million funding for ECS spin-out Perpetuum</a></h3><p>ECS spin-out company Perpetuum has attracted £2.2 million in further investment. Perpetuum produces innovative micro-generators which harvest energy from vibrations, to provide power without batteries or external electrical supplies. Perpetuum's patented technology was developed in ECS by a team led by Professor Neil White.</p><p></p></div><hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/866"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_866_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=8901510db2ada7e609c85a7b55254231&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Harvey Rutt, Ken Frampton, Dave Richardson" title="Harvey Rutt, Ken Frampton, Dave Richardson (Copyright: Steve Shrimpton)" border="0" width="94" height="120" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/866">New glass fibre machine aims to speed up internet communication</a></h3><p>A new machine to manufacture glass fibres which will be the best in the world could speed up the way messages are communicated through the Internet. Glass fibres with tiny holes through them have many uses, even manipulating light to enable messages to find their own way through the Internet. The new machine will be developed in the ECS mechanical workshop by Professor Harvey Rutt, Ken Frampton, and Professor David Richardson.</p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/864"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_864_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=687daaae415bad5fe577e847d9711fd3&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Participants in the MMS course" title="Participants in the MMS course" border="0" width="120" height="90" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/864">Motorola sponsor undergraduate Multimedia Systems Conference</a></h3><p>This year’s undergraduate Multimedia Systems Conference was voted a great success, not just by the student participants and their lecturers, but also by the event’s sponsors, Motorola Automotive. The annual conference forms a major part of the School’s final-year Computer Science course in Multimedia Systems. Students have the ambitious task of organizing and running a day-long conference, which showcases their own research findings in the form of presented papers.</p></div><hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/858"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_858_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=59680a5084da2e9cc4b3984770b66aba&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Vladimiro Sassone" title="Vladimiro Sassone" border="0" width="80" height="120" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/858">New Professor to develop ubiquitous computing</a></h3><p>A new Professor in the School of Electronics & Computer Science (ECS) is working towards making global computing a dependable reality. Professor Vladimiro Sassone, previously Head of the Department of Informatics at the University of Sussex, has joined ECS to help raise the School's profile and promote its external visibility in theoretical computer science.</p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/855"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_855_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=e7f478971ded7ab52eee62a4b0fd8149&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Provenance project logo" title="Provenance project logo (Copyright: Provenance)" border="0" width="60" height="120" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/855">Building trust and validation into distributed computer networks</a></h3><p>The School of Electronics and Computer Science is a leading partner in a European research project which will build trust and validation into distributed computer networks. The EU Provenance project will enable users of Grids—networks of computers at distributed locations–to understand the process by which a particular result was generated. This is fundamental to many real-life applications in science, engineering, medicine, and supply chain management.</p></div><p class="clearBoth"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20060223082346/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/">More News</a></p><br style="clear: both;" />
